Comment: Some people didn't enjoy this movie.  I myself was about to turn off the television after seeing the crashing waves of water in the beginning of the film for a couple of minutes lol. I am Mexican though and I could relate and having basic understanding of the Mexican culture helped me understand the message of the movie 100%.  I think that ROMA was one of those movies that you truly love and admire or totally hate.  There is no in between.  I have seen some movies filmed in Hollywood though that are based on historical or cultural events of the USA or different countries of the world and I end up being bored simply because I don't understand the history or culture of the country that the film is about.

Title: ROMA | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment:
Just watched it. Very clearly a very personal movie for the director. First half is...slow. Like I feel like I'm missing something slow. I get that it's showing what life was like back then, establishing characters but even with that going on nothing is still happening. Second half is..more interesting as you start to wonder just how much effort went into making those shots, they truly are amazing. There was a certain space movie part, that made me laugh out loud. End is pretty moving, liked it, which at least is worth it to watch the whole movie again. 
     Calling this an automatic masterpiece is annoying though. It feels like watching real people, but watching real people is boring as fuck unless they themselves are interesting or the situation around them makes them do interesting things.(The second half of the movie had those things).
I've seen enough indie movies to get annoyed at filmmakers showing me regular people doing mundane things and calling it art. I don't want car chases, non-stop action, every character is a black lesbian looking to change into a spaceman. But I have my limits.
I liked the movie, but it annoys to no end that there are people, who say it's pure magic or they just say it's shit. There IS a middle ground for fucks sake.

This is one of those trailers that really mis-leads.  The epic music, the quick cuts - and then the movie is anything but.  I know that ROMA is getting praised as an awesome experience of cinema, but really though - the story is certainly compelling and deep in it's simplicity and raw humanness, but the shots were only decent and the pace is so extremely slow without much happening.   I don't need every movie experience to be action packed by any means, but to watch long, slow scenes that don't seem to have any bearing on the overall story?
I'll try this movie again later on, but for now, I must be missing something.

In the 70s in Mexico, Cleo is a live-in maid to a wealthy family with four kids. It becomes clear that the father, Antonio, has left the family for another woman and Sofia, the mother, is pretending to the children like he‚Äôs coming back any day.

Meanwhile, Cleo becomes pregnant by her boyfriend Fermin, but when she tells him he abandons her. When she later tracks him down, he threatens her and says the baby isn‚Äôt his.

Eventually, Cleo has a stillborn baby. Sofia takes Cleo and the kids on a weekend vacation where she tells the children the truth, they are sad, but Sofia promises things will be okay. The next day Cleo saves two of the children from drowning, and they are incredibly grateful, but she admits she feels guilty for never having wanted the baby. The family returns home, now with Antonio‚Äôs things gone, and adjusts to their new way of life together.

Title: ROMA | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment:
Puedo resumir en tres palabras lo que para mi significo esta pelicula:
aburrida y sobrevalorada.
Desafortunadamente Los Oscares estan ahora en la linea de lo "politicamente correcto", como cuando en el a√±o 2017 en los Estados Unidos la comunidad afrodecendiente se rasgaba las vestiduras porque en los premios de la academia no los tenian en cuenta e hicieron severo escandalo.  Oh sorpresa, El Oscar para la Mejor Pelicula se lo otorgaron a "Moonlight" en vez de a "La la land".

Asi es de esperarse que este a√±o de las 10 nominaciones que tiene "Roma", por mal que le vaya, minimo se lleve el Oscar a Mejor Pelicula Extranjera (esto como un gui√±o para los mexicanos, ya que los gringos les han dado tan duro desde lo del muro).

"Roma" estaba vendida para la plataforma NETFLIX, pero Cuaron queria que participara en Los Oscares.
Los Academy Awards exige que una pelicula que quiera participar en el concurso tiene que ser exhibida en salas de cine tradicionales (y no solo en plataformas virtuales como era el caso), asi que Cuaron la exhibio 6 veces (creo que las 6 fueron en Mexico; pero repito solo fue un simple formalismo burocratico, para que la aceptaran en Los Oscares).

La formula para ganar El Oscar es esta:
...noveles directores, atenta nota...

Cuaron envuelve la pelicula en una fotografia preciosista y evocadora en blanco y negro (a lo Tarkovsky), con un montaje y un ritmo cadencioso (a lo Bergman) y nos sumerge en una historia que atrapa gustos sensibiliceros (a lo Corin Tellado); haciendo las delicias de los cineclubistas donde la comentaran con largas y entretenidas discuciones (me imagino alguna de esas charlas, hablando sobre que es lo que significa el indigenismo en la posmodernidad).

Asi que Mexico, ya pueden ir destapando el tequila porque este 24 de febrero van estar ganando minimo un Oscar; por mal que les vaya (vuelvo y repito).

Pido disculpas si hiero susceptibilidades.
No era mi intencion.

Comment: If you took out the swearing and the A-list name of Alfonso Curon, you could easily trick someone into thinking that this is a film from the early 70s. It has right wing Cristian values that don't exist in modern cinema and is told in an incredibly slow old fashioned way. So much so, that if Curon hadn't fully produced it himself, I doubt it would've gotten made. It's a great film that really gets in your head and if this wins Best Picture, then it'll put the hard-left identity politics in the otherwise excellent Shape of Water, out in the cold. Well for 5 minutes that is.

Title: ROMA | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment:
This is my honest opinion, so please don't be angry. 
( This first part is ONLY about the first 45 minutes to the first hour)
The usage of black and white can either make the movie more meaningful like, schindlers list, or completely wipe any emotions you had and or shared with any of the characters. Also when speaking about the black and white choice instead of color, there is a difference when using a light black and white overtone and a darker one. A lighter one has more of an aesthetic feeling, and is also used in photography, unlike a darker black and white overtone which is more realistic. This movie went for more of an aesthetic overtone, and that, while looking pretty, did not give off any real feelings. I understand it can be because of the time period, but if you have no real reason for it, don't use it. Also the movie, especially in the beginning, just dragged on and on without any major conflicts or anything happening. Also the use of no music was maybe not the best choice. I do understand that this isn't just any movie, that it's more authentic more real, that no music and a black and white screen can help you pay more attention to the characters. But, when choosing non actors, sometimes it can be hard for them to deliver real emotions. I will say they did an amazing job, but I felt no connection, or any sort of real feelings towards the characters. I did feel bad about when her boyfriend left her in the movie theatre. But every time after about five minutes after the scene ended I just forgot about it. I will say that after the first 45 minutes I did start to enjoy it more. The characters were more developed, but I still didn't like it. I don't think I'll watch this again but I'll make sure to recommend to to my friends and family.

Title: ROMA | Official Trailer [HD] | Netflix
Comment:
As a Mexican who grew up in Mexico city at the turn of the century, this brings back memories of a long gone time, all my childhood is inside those streets, from "La Roma", Downtown near Metropolitan Cinema now turned into a Show center/ Theater / Concert hall, it is funny how most of the ambience is so well pictured that it's almost as taking a time machine back to that time...
the story has no conductive line but that's just how life goes on w/o looking much into details and people we met are just a small part of our current life and time stories are subtly interwoven and cross paths here and there affecting our surroundings and our life as well...
I must say i felt like being there as part of the movie and even when this goes for over two hours I had the need for it to keep going...
Stereo stations long gone, Banks, ads, everything was too perfect as I remember part of my childhood...
